{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15678"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15678"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.75,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62218"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8369"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47664"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7027"},{"type":"tags","id":"7029"},{"type":"tags","id":"8523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62218"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about a small, painful lump on her external genitalia. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 mm tender, yellowish papule on the thin, pink, hairless fold of skin lateral to her vaginal opening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vulva","Vestibule of vagina","Labia minora","Vestibular bulb","Labia majora"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a likely blocked sebaceous gland in the labia minora. The anatomical description of a thin, pink, hairless fold of skin lateral to the vaginal opening is characteristic of this structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabia minora\u003C/strong\u003E are thin, pigmented, hairless folds of skin that extend from the clitoris anteriorly to meet posteriorly at the fourchette. They contain numerous sebaceous glands but lack hair follicles and sweat glands. They are highly innervated and have a rich blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evulva\u003C/strong\u003E refers to all the external female genitalia collectively, including the mons pubis, labia majora, labia minora, clitoris, and vestibule. This term is too general to be the most specific answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibule of vagina\u003C/strong\u003E is the space between the labia minora, containing the vaginal and urethral openings. It is lined by non-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium and would not typically develop sebaceous cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibular bulbs\u003C/strong\u003E are paired masses of erectile tissue located deep to the labia minora. As deep structures, they would not be visible on external examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elabia majora\u003C/strong\u003E are the outer hair-bearing folds that contain sweat glands, sebaceous glands, and adipose tissue. They have a darker, rugose appearance and would not match the description given in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The labia minora are highly innervated, thin, hairless folds of skin that extend from the clitoris to the vaginal opening.","The labia minora contain numerous sebaceous glands but no hair follicles or sweat glands.","The vestibular bulbs are erectile tissue located deep to the labia minora."],"references":["Yavagal S, de Farias TF, Medina CA, Takacs P. Normal vulvovaginal, perineal, and pelvic anatomy with reconstructive considerations. Semin Plast Surg. 2011 May;25(2):121-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1281481. PMID: 22547969; PMCID: PMC3312145.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47664"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47664"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T13:01:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T13:02:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8369"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62218"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"